snippet.textDisplay: @Lord Fendleberry: Episode I: Pod Racer also had real music. Unfortunately, both games’ music were heavily compressed and shortened, but I liked them still far more than say the digital score in Rogue Squadron. Factor 5 was praised for their music technology for the N64 and later Game Cube games, but I wasn’t impressed with their synthy soundtracks—especially the odd combined real John Williams OST with synthetic parts in the Rogue Leader games. The only other games I can think of that had (heavily compressed) real music were WipeOut 64 (with loading times as a result) and Killer Instinct Gold.

snippet.textDisplay:
I remember SotE awesome game back when it came out. The Hoth battle gave me goose bumps and the fight with Boba Fett left a good memory. Sadly the gameplay was so-so in 1996 standards and god awful in 2012 standards. I think they should released the game in a HD remake.

Also without this game you'd never have any newer star wars games likes SWTOR, Knights of the Old Republic, or Jedi knight games. It was a test for Lucas to see if the SW games could sell outside the movie base games.
